posts.name: Mr. Siefen | 453
posts.cooked:
This should be a digital input

The roboRIO’s FPGA supports up to 26 digital inputs. 10 of these are made available through the built-in DIO ports on the RIO itself, while the other 16 are available through the MXP breakout port....

The high or low value from the sensor when it’s tripped will depend on what you choose pnp or npn for wiring from the datasheet

As far as stopping a note at a set point @brandonmcd did something similar for ours with an analog distance sensor as the input.

With this sensor you will need to check what level of voltage is coming from the load lines as it operates on 12vdc not 5vdc. The DIO is meant for 5v signals. Npn would be better

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
As mentioned above the sensor is a digital input. It takes power from your 12v supply - according to the data sheet blue is - and brown is +12V.

Connect the blue to the a digital input ground (optional according to the diagram posted above since all the grounds are in common) and pick either the black or white to the Signal. Your choice for NC or NO (normally closed or normally open).

You can read the DIO wherever you want to. Any architecture can be made to work. Without code nobody can give you help on the lack of deploy except that not deploying usually means you have compile errors. The deploy/build tells you the error but you didn’t share that with us.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
Silversloth2848:

My team plugged it into analog instead of DIO, not entirely sure why, but it worked.

An NPN sensors works by shorting or not the DIO S to ground.

You likely have a PNP sensors which presents or not the higher voltage (the sensor’s power supply).

You can make a voltage divider circuit to drop the sensor’s working voltage to the level of the roboRIO analog input then detect if you see voltage or not.

Another thing I’ve seen is teams using the 5V power supply for a 10-30V sensor. Sometimes the sensor will work but very weakly - too weak to pass the digital input threshold for on so reading the analog input can detect a lower voltage to be used for the trigger.
